Stellera chamaejasme
L. is a perennial herb belonging to the plant family, Thymelaeaceae , and is mainly distributed in Northwest ( Gansu , Ningxia , Qinghai , Shaanxi , and Xinjiang ), Southwest ( Sichuan , Xizang , and Yunnan ), Northeast ( Heilongjiang , Jilin , and Liaoning ), North ( Hebei , Nei Mongol , and Shanxi ), and Central China ( Henan ) (
). Besides , this plant species is also found in Bhutan, Mongolia , Nepal , and Russia (
). In China , the roots of
S. chamaejasme
are traditionally used as a medicine called “Langdu”, widely acclaimed for multiple pharmacological actions such as the relief of cough, elimination of bloating, treatment of long-term accumulation of food and sputum, and for curing of scabies and diarrhea (
). Such beneficial medicinal attributes compelled the natural medicinal chemists to systematically study the chemical composition of “Langdu” and found that it was rich in flavonoids, diterpenoids, lignans, and coumarins (
;
;
). Recently , a number of guaiane sesquiterpenoids and their derivatives (including 2,3- seco -, 3,4- seco -, 8,9- seco -, 1,10- seco -, 10,11-cyclo-, and 1, 12-cyclo-guaianes) have been found in the roots of
S. chamaejasme
(
,
;
;
;
;
;
;
), their structures have been enlisted in
Figs. S1.1 S1.2
and
Table S1.1
(Supplementary data). Furthermore, in vivo and in vitro bioactivity evaluation demonstrated that the crude extracts and chemical components of
S. chamaejasme
possessed potential anti-viral, anti-bacterial, anti-convulsive, anti-epileptic, anti-inflammation, anti-tumor, neuroprotective, and insecticide properties (
,
;
;
;
, 2021).

In the course of our continuing work of discovering structurally intriguing and neuroprotective agents from natural sources (
;
;
;
), chemical investigation of the roots of
S. chamaejasme
led to the isolation of 20 sesquiterpenoids with various structures including 14 guaianes, four carotanes, a sesquicarane, and one alpiniane. Among these, compounds 1–6 were undescribed ones, whose structures were determined by analysis of their spectroscopic and the Mo 2 (OAc) 4 -induced ECD data together with the utilization of 1D NMR and ECD calculation methods. In the sodium nitroprusside (SNP)-induced PC-12 cell (pheochromocytoma cell line) model, compounds 1–20 were screened for their neuroprotective effects on cell damage and the possible mechanisms of neuroprotection of the most active compound were further explored. Herein, details of the isolation, structural elucidation, and neuroprotective effects of these sesquiterpenoids are reported.

The molecular formula of compound 6 was determined to be C 15 H 26 O 2 by the HRESIMS ion at m / z 261.1828 [M + Na] + (calcd 261.1825) and its 1D NMR data. The 1 H NMR data ( Table 3 ) displayed signals for four tertiary methyls [ δ H 1.58, 1.20, 1.15, and 0.72 (each 3H, s)], an olefinic proton [ δ H 5.22 (1H, br. s)], an oxygenated methine [ δ H 3.29 (1H, d, J =10.1 Hz)], and two high-field methine protons [ δ H 0.76 and 0.62 (each 1H, m)]. The observed 15 carbon signals in the 13 C NMR spectrum were classified into four methyls, a trisubstituented double bond, four methylenes, three methines (including an oxygenated one), and two quaternary carbons (including an oxygenated one) according to the DEPT experiments. As shown in Fig. 2 , two fragments CH (3) CH 2 (2) CH (1) CH (6) CH 2 (5) and CH 2 (8) CH 2 (9) CH (10) were confirmed by the 1 H– 1 H COSY correlations. According to the HMBC correlations from H 3 -15 to C-3, C-4, and C-5, H 3 -14 to C-1, C-6, C-7, and C-8, and H 3 -12(13) to C-10 and C-11 ( Fig. 2 ), the aforementioned two fragments, four methyls ( CH 3 -12/13/14/15), and three quaternary carbons (C-4/7/11) were constructed to form a sesquicarane-type sesquiterpenoid. The key NOE correlations of H-1/H-8a and H-6/H-8a suggested that H-1, H-6, and the C-8 chain were cofacial and randomly assigned as β -oriented, indicating the CH 3 -14 to be α -oriented ( Fig. 3 ). In addition, the 10 S configuration of 6 was determined by the Mo 2 (OAc) 4 - induced ECD experiment (
;
), which displayed the positive Cotton effect at 316 nm (Δ ε +2.32) (
Fig.
S 1.6
in Supplementary data). Thus, the structure of 6 was determined as shown and given a trivial name sesquistrachanoid F.

