In SNP-induced PC-12 cell model, nerve cells damage was caused by reactive oxygen species (ROS)-mediated oxidative stress (
;
), thus we explored the effect of 11 on this biological process. As shown in Fig. 6C and Table 4 , when the PC-12 cells were exposed to SNP, some indicators related to oxidative stress have changed significantly. For example, the levels of ROS and malonic dialdehyde (MDA) showed a remarkable increase, while the levels of glutathione (GSH) and superoxide dismutase (SOD) were substantially reduced. Meanwhile, the intervention of SNP could also lead to the loss of mitochondrial membrane potential (MMP) ( Fig. 6D ). Such abnormal changes in the aforementioned indicators caused by SNP could be significantly reversed by the pretreatment of 11 ( Fig. 6C and D and Table 4 ), which therefore suggests that 11 could play a protective role by reducing oxidative stress.
